04431nam a22005055i 9780773569348DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735693487 a10.1515/97807735693482doi  a(DE-B1597)654490  a(OCoLC)76898623  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE92bH39 2001eb 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a971.01/81 aHavard, Gilles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGreat Peace of Montreal of 1701 :bFrench-Native Diplomacy in the Seventeenth Century /cGilles Havard. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (320 p.) :billus., maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChronology -- tIntroduction -- tKey Elements of Amerindian Diplomacy -- tAlliances and Strategies in the Late Seventeenth Century -- tWars and Peace in the Seventeenth Century -- tIroquois Delegations and Colonial Rivalries -- tAccommodation and Confrontation in the West -- tOn the Path to Montreal, 1700–1701 -- tMontreal, Capital of Peace: 21 July to 7 August 1701 -- tThe Tree of Peace -- t1701: A New Situation -- tConclusion -- tThe Nature of the Treaty and the Amerindian Pictographs -- tThe Cast of Characters in the Great Peace of Montreal -- tEnglish Translation of the Montreal Treaty of 1701 -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tGlossary of the Names of Native Peoples -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe last decades of the seventeenth century were marked by persistent, bloody conflicts between the French and their Native allies on the one side and the Iroquois confederacy on the other. In the summer of 1701, 1,300 representatives of forty First Nations from the Maritimes to the Great Lakes and from James Bay to southern Illinois met with the French at Montreal. Elaborate, month-long ceremonies culminated in the signing of The Great Peace of Montreal, which effectively put an end to the Iroquois wars. In The Great Peace of Montreal of 1701 Gilles Havard brings to life the European and Native players who brought about this major feat of international diplomacy. He highlights the differing interests and strategies of the numerous First Nations involved while giving a dramatic account of the colourful conference. The treaty, Havard argues, was the culmination of the French colonial strategy of Native alliances and adaptation to Native political customs. It illustrates the extent of cultural interchange between the French and their Native allies and the crucial role the latter played in French conflicts with the Iroquois and the British. As we approach the 300th anniversary of the treaty's signing in August 1701, Gilles Havard emphasizes its contemporary significance: in signing a treaty with forty separate parties the French recognized the independent sovereignty of every First Nation. This translation is significantly revised and updated from the original French publication of 1992.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356934840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773569348423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773569348/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles